title: Sanctuary of the South (SOS) Town Hall - Defend and Uplift Immigrant Communities
description:
Come together with us for an urgent and powerful evening of community, conversation, and resistance.

Founded by seasoned civil rights leaders, Sanctuary of the South (SOS) is more than an organization—it’s a movement. SOS exists to build justice and liberation through communal love, support, and resistance. We serve immigrant, LGBTQ+, and BIPOC communities throughout the South by providing low bono legal services, community sanctuary spaces, and seed funding for grassroots projects. We are a refuge—a place to heal, to organize, and to build the world we deserve.

At this Town Hall, we’ll come together to:

-Build community and exchange ideas on what this moment in history demands of us

-Share tangible ways to fight back against the rise of authoritarianism

-Explore how to protect our people—immigrants, queer and trans folks, Black and brown communities—through mutual support and collective action

-Invite you into the SOS ecosystem, where there is no divide between the work and the people it serves

SOS explicitly rejects the nonprofit industrial complex, refusing all state and major foundation funding. We answer only to our people—not to funders, not to boards. That makes us nimble, real, and grounded in what truly matters.

If you’ve been looking for a movement home rooted in the South and powered by fierce love, this is your invitation. You are welcome here. SOS is for you. It is for all of us.

Let’s gather, let’s organize, and let’s build together.

RSVP now and join us.

description:

We want to make sure that rural West Tennesseans aren't push out of their homes and that everyone can benefit from the economic growth that Blue Oval City has promised. 

For the past two years, Blue Oval Good Neighbors has been calling on Blue Oval SK to come to the table for a Community Benefits Agreement that can secure community investments for generations to come not just for right now or while the EV industry is trending. One of the biggest issues we've identified has been housing, we want to see funding for free legal representation for evicted tenants, relocation allowances for folks who have to relocate due to rising costs and property tax subsidies for home-owners. 

Join us on Saturday, June 7 from 11AM-1PM for an important community discussion on the state of affordable housing in rural West Tennessee and what we can do together to prevent gentrification and preserve the legacy of rural West Tennessee. Lunch will be provided.

title: Medicaid Budget Cut Panel Discussion
description:
🔥We are facing a national crisis. Congress is selling us out by slashing Medicaid, SNAP funding, and more. Why? To give more tax cuts to billionaires.

💸 But the services they’re slashing aren’t theirs—they’re ours. Our communities are paying the price while the Trumps and Musks of the world cash in. It’s not just about money—it’s about power. Trump’s administration is targeting everybody who isn’t part of the 1%—veterans, kids, seniors, farmers, immigrants, transgender people, and political opponents. All to consolidate power and reward their allies.

On Feb. 25th, Representative Jeff Crank voted to move forward with H. Con. Res. 14 which cuts Medicaid benefits in order to give billionaires a tax cut.  According to Rep. Crank “I think there’s groups out there that are trying to scare people… to try and scare people into believing that there’s going to be all these massive Medicaid cuts. And that hasn’t been the case, that’s not the intention of anybody here, is to cut people off of Medicaid.”   However, H. Con. Res. 14 calls for cuts of $880 billion over the next decade from the House Energy and Commerce Committee, which oversees health care spending programs including Medicaid and Medicare. 

·         Data shows 19% of Crank’s 5th Congressional District are enrolled in Medicaid
·         Medicaid covers 6 in 10 nursing home residents
·         1,174,868 people in Colorado are on Medicaid
·         Medicaid covers 1 in 3 children in Colorado.
·         36% of births in CO are covered by Medicaid
·         65% of adults in CO on Medicaid are working
·         55% of non-elderly Medicaid enrollees in CO are people of color

description:
